u$ and braking torque $K 
u^{n_{m pl}}$, features secular and stochastic anomalies arising from $\dot{K} 
eq 0$ and random torque noise respectively. Previous studies quantified the variance $\langle n^{2} angle = (n_{m pl}+\dot{K}_{m dim})^{2}+\sigma_{m dim}^{2}$, where the secular anomaly, $\dot{K}_{m dim}$, is inversely proportional to the characteristic time-scale $	au_{K}$ over which $K$ varies; the stochastic anomaly, $\sigma_{m dim}^{2} = \sigma_{\ddot{
u}}^{2}
u^{2}\gamma_{\ddot{
u}}^{-2}\dot{
u}^{-4}T_{m obs}^{-1}$, is a function of the timing noise amplitude $\sigma_{\ddot{
u}}$, a damping time-scale $\gamma_{\ddot{
u}}^{-1}$ and the total observing time $T_{m obs}$; and the average is taken over an ensemble of random realizations of the noise process. Here, we use a hierarchical Bayesian scheme, based on the formula for $\langle n^{2} angle$, to infer the population-level distribution of $n_{m pl}+\dot{K}_{m dim}$ for a sample of $68$ young radio pulsars, observed for $\gtrsim 10~{m years}$ with Murriyang, the 64-m Parkes radio telescope. Upon assuming that the $n_{m pl}+\dot{K}_{m dim}$ values are drawn from a population-level Gaussian, $N(\mu_{m pl}, \sigma_{m pl})$, the Bayesian scheme returns the mean $\mu_{m pl} = 9.95^{+5.58}_{-5.26}$ and standard deviation $\sigma_{m pl}=10.89^{+5.14}_{-3.69}$. At a per-pulsar level it returns posterior medians satisfying $-13.86 \leq n_{m pl}+\dot{K}_{m dim} \leq 30.38$. The secular anomaly dominates the stochastic anomaly, with posterior medians satisfying $|n_{m pl} + \dot{K}_{m dim}| \geq \sigma_{m dim}$ in 10 out of 68 objects.

With the potential prospects of the $D^{*}_{s}$ at high-luminosity heavy-flavor experiments in the future, we investigated the CKM-favored and tree-dominated leptonic $D^{*}_{s}	o\ell ar{
u}_{\ell}$ and semileptonic $D^{*}_{s}	o M\ell ar{
u}_{\ell}$ ($M=\phi, \eta^{(\prime)}$ and $\ell=e, \mu$) weak decays in the Standard Model (SM). The theoretical predictions and some discussions for the observable quantities including the total width of $D^{*}_{s}$ mesons, the branching fractions of leptonic $D^{*}_{s}	o\ell ar{
u}_{\ell}$ and semileptonic $D^{*}_{s}	o M\ell ar{
u}_{\ell}$ weak decays, the lepton spin asymmetry and forward-backward asymmetry are presented. Numerically, the weak decays of $D^{*}_{s}	o\ell ar{
u}_{\ell}$ and $D^{*}_{s} 	o M\ell ar{
u}_{\ell}$ have relatively large branching fractions of the order $\mathcal{O}(10^{-5})$ and $\mathcal{O}(10^{-7})$ respectively, which are expected to be observed in future experiments.
